\par\par \uc2 Business/Financial Desk; SECTB\par \b \uc2 Executives Traded Frantic Texts as Crypto Collapsed\b0\par\par\uc2 By David Yaffe-Bellany and Emily Flitter \par \uc2 1,042 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 December 2022\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2022 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 A group chat including crypto leaders shows \uc2 Binance\uc2 's \uc2 Changpeng Zhao\uc2  accusing FTX's \uc2 Sam Bankman-Fried\uc2  of orchestrating trades to destabilize the industry.\par \par \uc2 The day before the embattled cryptocurrency exchange FTX filed for bankruptcy, \uc2 Changpeng Zhao\uc2 , the chief executive of the rival exchange \uc2 Binance\uc2 , sent an alarmed text to \uc2 Sam Bankman-Fried\uc2 , FTX's founder.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Zhao was concerned that Mr. Bankman-Fried was orchestrating crypto trades that could send the industry into a meltdown. ''Stop now, don't cause more damage,'' Mr. Zhao wrote in a group chat with Mr. Bankman-Fried and other crypto executives on Nov. 10. ''The more damage you do now, the more jail time.''\par \par \uc2 FTX and its sister hedge fund, \uc2 Alameda Research\uc2 , had just collapsed after a run on deposits exposed an $8 billion hole in the exchange's accounts. The implosion unleashed a crypto crisis, as firms with ties to FTX teetered on the brink of bankruptcy, calling the future of the entire industry into question.\par \par \uc2 The series of about a dozen group texts between Mr. Zhao and Mr. Bankman-Fried on Nov. 10, which were obtained by \uc2 The New York Times\uc2 , show that key crypto leaders feared that the situation could get even worse. And their frantic communications offer a rare glimpse into the unusual way business is conducted behind the scenes in the industry, with at least three top officials from rival companies exchanging messages in a group chat on the encrypted messaging app Signal.\par \par \uc2 The texts also show that industry leaders were acutely aware that the actions of a single firm or fluctuations in the value of one virtual currency could destabilize the whole industry. The exchanges became increasingly tense as Mr. Bankman-Fried and Mr. Zhao traded barbs.\par \par \uc2 Earlier that week, Mr. Zhao had agreed to buy FTX and save the exchange, before backing out of the deal. In the Nov. 10 texts, he appeared certain that FTX would not survive, and concerned that it could bring the rest of the industry down with it. During a crypto crash in May, two currencies had plunged in value, setting off an industrywide meltdown and forcing several prominent firms into bankruptcy.\par \par \uc2 In the Nov. 10 texts, Mr. Zhao specifically accused Mr. Bankman-Fried of using his hedge fund to drive down the price of Tether, a so-called stablecoin whose price is designed to remain at $1. According to messages seen by The Times and people familiar with the matter, the group chat included several other prominent crypto executives, including \uc2 Jesse Powell\uc2 , a founder of the crypto exchange Kraken, and Paolo Ardoino, the chief technology officer of Tether, the company that issues the stablecoin of the same name.\par \par \uc2 Tether is a linchpin of crypto trading worldwide, commonly used by digital asset enthusiasts to conduct transactions. Industry insiders have long feared that if Tether's price fell, it would cause a domino effect that might bring the industry to its knees. (Tether ultimately did not end up losing its $1 peg.)\par \par \uc2 A spokeswoman for \uc2 Binance\uc2  declined to comment on the text exchanges. A spokeswoman for Kraken declined to comment.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Bankman-Fried, 30, said in a statement that Mr. Zhao's claims were ''absurd.''\par \par \uc2 ''Trades of that size would not make a material impact on Tether's pricing, and to my knowledge neither myself nor Alameda has ever attempted to intentionally depeg Tether or any other stablecoins,'' he said. ''I have made a number of mistakes over the past year but this is not one of them.''\par \par \uc2 A spokeswoman for Tether said in a statement that the company had ''demonstrated its resilience to attacks.'' She added that FTX's actions ''don't reflect the ethos and commitment of an entire industry.''\par \par \uc2 FTX, a marketplace where people could buy and sell digital currencies, collapsed early last month when customers rushed to withdraw deposits, partly in response to tweets by Mr. Zhao that called the company's finances into question. FTX soon folded, setting off investigations by the Justice Department and the \uc2 Securities and Exchange Commission\uc2  into whether the crypto exchange broke the law by using its customers' funds to prop up Alameda.\par \par \uc2 The Justice Department is also investigating whether Mr. Bankman-Fried engaged in market manipulation in the spring by making trades that contributed to the failure of two prominent cryptocurrencies.\par \par \uc2 For years, critics of the crypto industry have said Tether could also be vulnerable to a collapse. Tether has long claimed that its stablecoins are backed by cash and other traditional assets, and that in a crisis, all of its customers could redeem their coins for the equivalent amount in dollars. But regulators have previously accused Tether of lying about the status of its reserves, sowing doubts about the coin's reliability.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Bankman-Fried was once a major Tether customer. Before he agreed to the deal with \uc2 Binance\uc2 , he met with a top Tether official in the Bahamas, where FTX was based, and asked for billions in funding to prop up his exchange, a person with knowledge of the matter said. Tether declined to help, the person said.\par \par \uc2 In one of the Nov. 10 messages to the group, Mr. Zhao pointed out a $250,000 trade by Alameda that he said was intended to destabilize Tether. The trade was visible on the \uc2 blockchain\uc2 , a public ledger of cryptocurrency transactions that anyone can view.\par \par \uc2 In response to Mr. Zhao's accusations, Mr. Bankman-Fried seemed nonplused. ''Huh?'' he said. ''What am I doing to stablecoins?''\par \par \uc2 ''Are you claiming that you think that $250k of USDT trading would depeg it?'' he added, using a common shorthand to refer to the Tether currency.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Zhao responded that he didn't think a trade of that size would succeed in destroying Tether, but that it could still cause problems.\par \par \uc2 ''My honest advice: stop doing everything,'' Mr. Zhao said. ''Put on a suit, and go back to DC, and start to answer questions.''\par \par \uc2 ''Thanks for the advice!'' Mr. Bankman-Fried shot back.\par \par \uc2 Changpeng Zhao, founder of Binance, was part of the group chat on Nov. 10. (PHOTOGRAPH BY COSTAS BALTAS/REUTERS) This article appeared in print on page B3. \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020221210eica0003x\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw284\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4260\pichgoal600
