\par\par \uc2 Business/Financial Desk; SECTB\par \b \uc2 After FTX, Crypto Sector Scrambles To Save Itself\b0\par\par\uc2 By David Yaffe-Bellany \par \uc2 1,629 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 December 2022\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2022 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 The implosion of the exchange FTX shows how an industry built in the wake of the 2008 financial crisis has drifted far from its original ideals.\par \par \uc2 To hear more audio stories from publications like \uc2 The New York Times\uc2 , download Audm for iPhone or Android .\par \par \uc2 Not long after several Wall Street banks collapsed in 2008, a nine-page document circulated on an obscure mailing list, proposing a new kind of financial system that wouldn't rely on any ''trusted third party.''\par \par \uc2 The paper was the basis for what became the cryptocurrency industry. Using sweeping, idealistic language, its adherents vowed to conduct business in a transparent and egalitarian way, rejecting the high-risk practices of a small number of powerful financial firms that caused the Great Recession.\par \par \uc2 But last month, the actions of a single crypto firm -- the $32 billion exchange FTX -- plunged the emerging industry into its own version of a 2008-style crisis. Once considered a safe marketplace for people to trade virtual currencies, FTX filed for bankruptcy after the crypto equivalent of a bank run, forcing industry executives, investors and enthusiasts to grapple with how a technology meant to correct the shortcomings of traditional finance ended up replicating them.\par \par \uc2 Executives who just a year ago were reveling amid crypto's seemingly unstoppable growth are now scrambling to prove that they can learn from the mistakes and recapture the industry's early ideals. \uc2 Binance\uc2 , the world's largest exchange, announced last month that it would release more information about its finances and recruit independent auditors to review those disclosures. \uc2 Coinbase\uc2 , the biggest U.S. crypto exchange, proclaimed that it was committed to a ''decentralized system where you don't have to trust us.''\par \par \uc2 Many crypto advocates are pushing for more drastic reforms, urging investors not to store their digital holdings with big companies and instead turn to more experimental platforms run solely by code.\par \par \uc2 But for all the promises of change, FTX's collapse shows how far crypto remains from fulfilling its original aims and gaining widespread acceptance. Consumer distrust has mounted this year amid major financial losses, criminal investigations and an increasingly skeptical regulatory climate in Washington. At a conference last month, \uc2 Changpeng Zhao\uc2 , \uc2 Binance\uc2 's chief executive, said that FTX's implosion would set the industry back by years.\par \par \uc2 The exchange's downfall compounded months of losses in the virtual currency market set off by a devastating crash in the spring that unfolded amid a broader pullback from risky assets. The upheaval sent some prominent crypto firms into bankruptcy. Bitcoin, the original and most popular cryptocurrency, has been trading at less than $17,000, down about 75 percent from its high of nearly $70,000 almost exactly a year ago.\par \par \uc2 ''You start to go through these problems, and they stack up one after the other after the other,'' said John Reed Stark, a former \uc2 Securities and Exchange Commission\uc2  official who has become an outspoken crypto critic. ''More and more people are seeing this for the scam that it is.''\par \par \uc2 The crypto industry has bounced back after previous crashes, attracting big-name investors who poured even more money into experimental companies. But FTX's collapse has been widely described as the worst moment in the industry's short history.\par \par \uc2 The origins of crypto date to 2008, when a mysterious figure known as \uc2 Satoshi Nakamoto\uc2  published a white paper on Bitcoin, laying out a detailed vision for what became cryptocurrencies. The paper outlined Bitcoin's technological foundation, which was a publicly viewable ledger called a \uc2 blockchain\uc2  where transactions would be recorded for all to see.\par \par \uc2 Early enthusiasts thought Bitcoin could become the foundation of a more transparent, egalitarian financial system. Many of the paper's supporters were libertarians who had grown disillusioned with traditional finance, especially the concentration of power among a small number of companies.\par \par \uc2 At first, crypto's primary use was criminal. Thieves and drug dealers used Bitcoin to transfer large amounts of money without relying on a bank or another intermediary to process transactions.\par \par \uc2 But over the years, law enforcement got better at tracking crypto crime, and the technology evolved to allow more sophisticated financial applications, like borrowing and lending. People who started their careers on Wall Street -- including FTX's founder, \uc2 Sam Bankman-Fried\uc2 , who worked at the trading firm Jane Street -- got involved in the nascent industry, looking to profit from the technology.\par \par \uc2 As the industry grew, it started assuming some of the same characteristics as the Wall Street institutions that it was designed to replace. Crypto trading became increasingly centralized, with a large portion of transactions taking place on a handful of big exchanges, including \uc2 Binance\uc2 , FTX and \uc2 Coinbase\uc2 . In the months leading up to FTX's collapse, the trading volume of cryptocurrencies on \uc2 Binance\uc2  alone was greater than the combined totals of its seven closest competitors, according to an industry data tracker.\par \par \uc2 The original vision of crypto ''was an attempt to rewrite the rules of finance on a global basis,'' said Charley Cooper, managing director at the \uc2 blockchain\uc2  company R3. ''And here we are again -- we're in an even more centralized industry than we'd see in banking.''\par \par \uc2 Cryptocurrencies soared in value last year and into 2022 -- until May. That was when a popular cryptocurrency called Luna crashed, sending the crypto economy into free-fall. Two major lending companies, \uc2 Celsius Network\uc2  and \uc2 Voyager Digital\uc2 , filed for bankruptcy. Enthusiasts lamented the onset of a ''crypto winter'' of depressed prices and fading enthusiasm.\par \par \uc2 Amid the crisis, FTX was considered a relatively trustworthy force. Based in the Bahamas, the company served as a marketplace for people to buy and sell cryptocurrencies, offering high-risk but popular trading options that are illegal in the United States. Mr. Bankman-Fried, 30, who had built FTX into a $32 billion company, bailed out struggling firms and built a reputation as a benevolent figure willing to extend a lifeline to colleagues.\par \par \uc2 Then last month, a run on deposits exposed an $8 billion hole in FTX's accounts. The company filed for bankruptcy within a week. The \uc2 Securities and Exchange Commission\uc2  and the Justice Department opened investigations, focused on whether FTX illegally lent its users' funds to \uc2 Alameda Research\uc2 , a crypto hedge fund that Mr. Bankman-Fried also founded and owned.\par \par \uc2 The implosion has been described as a ''Lehman moment'' for crypto, a reference to the investment bank whose implosion helped set off the 2008 financial crisis. Other companies with ties to FTX started to teeter. Last Monday, the crypto lender BlockFi, one of the companies that FTX had bailed out in the spring, filed for bankruptcy, citing its entanglements with Mr. Bankman-Fried.\par \par \uc2 Some prominent figures in crypto have tried spinning FTX's downfall as a positive development, arguing that it will redirect energy toward finding practical uses for the technology.\par \par \uc2 ''For us, this is actually a great moment,'' said \uc2 Jeremy Allaire\uc2 , the chief executive of the crypto payments company Circle. ''We're delivering real value, and the people who focused on building giant speculative trading casinos are not so happy.''\par \par \uc2 Binance\uc2  operates essentially the same type of business as FTX, but Mr. Zhao, the chief executive, has recently been careful to differentiate himself from Mr. Bankman-Fried, calling his one-time rival a liar and criticizing FTX's most dangerous practices. On Nov. 25, \uc2 Binance\uc2  announced a new ''proof of reserves system,'' promising to keep users informed about the amount of cryptocurrency in its accounts and to dispel fears that it might be vulnerable to the type of run on deposits that destroyed FTX. (But \uc2 Binance\uc2 's plans were heavily criticized for lacking key information.)\par \par \uc2 Coinbase\uc2  has also tried to alleviate fears of a collapse, publishing a blog post that said it always holds the same amount of money that customers deposited. ''There can't be a 'run on the bank' at \uc2 Coinbase\uc2 ,'' the post said.\par \par \uc2 Still, the mere existence of large companies like \uc2 Binance\uc2 , \uc2 Coinbase\uc2  and FTX is antithetical to the ideals of crypto, some industry experts argue. Since FTX's collapse, some crypto enthusiasts have flocked to smaller firms in the experimental field of decentralized finance, which allows traders to borrow, lend and conduct transactions without banks or brokers, relying instead on a publicly viewable system governed by code.\par \par \uc2 But \uc2 DeFi\uc2  has its own problems, including vulnerability to hackers, who have drained billions of dollars this year from the experimental projects.\par \par \uc2 ''They've based it on clunky technology that is very inefficient,'' said Hilary Allen, a finance expert at \uc2 American University\uc2 . ''They're operationally very fragile.''\par \par \uc2 Scrutiny in Washington has also intensified. \uc2 Gary Gensler\uc2 , the chair of the S.E.C., has vowed to pursue crypto companies for violations of securities law. The \uc2 House Financial Services Committee\uc2  is scheduled to hold a hearing on Dec. 13 examining FTX's collapse.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Bankman-Fried has been asked to testify. In interviews with \uc2 The New York Times\uc2 , he has at times seemed agonized over FTX's bankruptcy -- and at times been strikingly flippant.\par \par \uc2 ''You know,'' he said in one interview, ''the crypto winter has been officially extended.''\par \par \uc2 Wasn't that a bit of an understatement? ''Yep,'' he replied. ''Alas.''\par \par \uc2 Audio produced by Parin Behrooz.\par \par \uc2 Audio produced by Parin Behrooz.\par \par \uc2 From top: FTX's founder, Sam Bankman-Fried, onscreen at the DealBook Summit 2022 in New York last week; Changpeng Zhao, C.E.O. of Binance, said FTX's collapse would set the industry back years; Gary Gensler, chair of the Securities and Exchange Commission, vowed to pursue crypto companies for securities law violations. (PHOTOGRAPHS BY HIROKO MASUIKE/THE NEW YORK TIMES; COSTAS BALTAS/REUTERS; SHURAN HUANG FOR THE NEW YORK TIMES) (B6) his article appeared in print on page B1, B6. \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020221207eic60000i\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw284\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4260\pichgoal600
