\par\par \uc2 Business/Financial Desk; SECTB\par \b \uc2 It's All and All Musk's Changing\b0\par\par\uc2 By Erin Griffith \par \uc2 1,151 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 October 2022\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2022 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 The way forward for \uc2 Twitter\uc2  is uncertain. But that means Mr. Musk can innovate and change the platform for the better, his supporters say.\par \par \uc2 Elon Musk\uc2  closes his purchase of \uc2 Twitter\uc2  and fires several top executives. Follow for the latest news updates .\par \par \uc2 Cryptocurrency enthusiasts are cheering for a decentralized social network. Supporters of Donald J. Trump hope that the former president will return to tweeting. Some free speech advocates envision an end to censorship. And loyal fans of \uc2 Elon Musk\uc2  are betting that the billionaire will innovate.\par \par \uc2 For these groups and others, \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's $44 billion sale to Mr. Musk, which closed on Thursday, is a moment to celebrate. The six-month path to buying (then attempting to back out of buying, then being sued into buying) the social network was a roller-coaster ride, a tragicomedy and, for many people involved in it, a waking nightmare.\par \par \uc2 But throughout the drama, the deal elicited a frisson of excitement from a wide swath of people for a range of reasons. By captivating celebrities, commentators and world leaders, \uc2 Twitter\uc2  has lodged itself into the fabric of society. The platform's future under Mr. Musk has become a symbolic receptacle of people's desires to push the world in the direction they want it to go.\par \par \uc2 Few tech executives elicit the kind of blind adoration that Mr. Musk does. His fans -- known variously as Muskies, Muskites, Muskrats and Musketeers -- defend even his most questionable moves. His deal to buy \uc2 Twitter\uc2  has had plenty of critics, including the company's employees, some lawmakers and disinformation researchers. Many fear what he will do with the platform, over which he now has more or less absolute power as its owner. But on Musk-focused message boards, Discord servers, blogs, podcasts and \uc2 YouTube\uc2  channels, the deal is a triumph.\par \par \uc2 ''Him buying \uc2 Twitter\uc2  is pretty awesome,'' said Bryce Paul, the host of the podcast ''Crypto 101.'' Mr. Paul does not consider himself a Musk fanboy but believes the billionaire is a ''genius'' and a ''modern-day da Vinci.''\par \par \uc2 Mr. Musk has discussed plans to transform \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , which has not found the business success of its social media competitors. The company's stock price has lagged, its user growth has stalled and its profits have been spotty. Since announcing his takeover plans in April, Mr. Musk has floated laying off \uc2 Twitter\uc2  employees, loosening the site's moderation policies, incorporating \uc2 blockchain\uc2  technology, charging subscription fees and making it into an ''everything app'' called X.\par \par \uc2 First Amendment scholars have cheered Mr. Musk's plans for less moderation on the platform, citing instances when \uc2 Twitter\uc2  banned users who had tweeted about pandemic policies or removed content, like a New York Post article about \uc2 Hunter Biden\uc2 's laptop, as censorship run amok.\par \par \uc2 ''\uc2 Twitter\uc2  is a tragic example of how censorship can become an insatiable appetite,'' said Jonathan Turley, a professor at the \uc2 George Washington University Law School\uc2 . ''Once you start to regulate speech, it's difficult to stop a natural expansion of that system. \uc2 Twitter\uc2  is a vivid example of that.''\par \par \uc2 Conservatives, some of whom claim \uc2 Twitter\uc2  has ''shadow-banned'' them (that is, hidden their tweets from followers without telling them), have also cheered Mr. Musk's takeover. Mr. Musk said in May that he would lift \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's ban on Mr. Trump.\par \par \uc2 Dinesh D'Souza, a conservative commentator, predicted that his \uc2 Twitter\uc2  following would double under Mr. Musk's ownership and egged on the potential layoffs. ''I think @elonmusk would do well to fire EVERYBODY and then carefully rehire the ones who share his vision of a free speech internet,'' Mr. D'Souza wrote this month.\par \par \uc2 Others are in favor of more transparency. Jano le Roux, the director of marketing at Likeflare, a marketing agency in the San Francisco Bay Area, said he was surprised that more people weren't in favor of the deal. He supported the possibility that Mr. Musk could expose more information about \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's algorithms, which determine which tweets find big audiences.\par \par \uc2 ''It's really important we put glass walls on what is, essentially, the messaging factory of the world,'' he said. Making the formulas of \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's algorithms public could benefit democracy, he added.\par \par \uc2 Cryptocurrency fans have also rhapsodized about the future of \uc2 Twitter\uc2  under Mr. Musk, who has participated in crypto culture by sharing memes on \uc2 Twitter\uc2  and cracking jokes about the virtual currency Dogecoin on ''Saturday Night Live.'' After Mr. Musk agreed to buy \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , he discussed various cryptocurrency integrations, including running the social media service on a decentralized \uc2 blockchain\uc2  network, according to text messages released as part of the legal fight over the deal.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Musk ultimately concluded that ''\uc2 blockchain\uc2 Twitter\uc2 '' wasn't possible and complained about having to endure ''laborious \uc2 blockchain\uc2  debate,'' according to his messages. But rumors about a different crypto solution under Mr. Musk -- digital currency wallets for \uc2 Twitter\uc2  users -- bubbled up this week.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Paul, the podcaster, said such a move could drive adoption of digital currencies.\par \par \uc2 ''You have the world's richest man, in some way, legitimizing some of our concepts and ideas, and it will be a fantastic onboarding platform,'' he said. The crypto world, he added, is generally pro-Musk.\par \par \uc2 ''I've heard very few dissenting opinions about Elon,'' he said.\par \par \uc2 In the days before the deal closed, some business leaders also made vaguely encouraging public comments about Mr. Musk, much as they might congratulate a new president.\par \par \uc2 Cathie Wood, the cryptocurrency investor, said in an interview with Yahoo Finance that she was ''excited'' to see Mr. Musk ''open up the ecosystem, take away the censorship, make it much more transparent and, I think, add more value.''\par \par \uc2 Jamie Dimon\uc2 , the chief executive of \uc2 JPMorgan Chase\uc2 , told CNBC that he hoped Mr. Musk ''cleans up \uc2 Twitter\uc2 '' by eliminating ''all those people in the public square who are robots and emails and stuff like that.''\par \par \uc2 When Mr. Musk tweeted a video of himself carrying a sink into \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's headquarters in San Francisco on Wednesday -- adding ''Let that sink in,'' a recurring joke on \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , to the post -- his fans responded with memes: Mr. Musk as Mr. Trump firing contestants on ''The Apprentice''; Mr. Musk as Thanos; Mr. Musk as Ari Gold (of ''Entourage''); and Mr. Musk as Drake.\par \par \uc2 Twitter\uc2  employees were less enthusiastic. Stephanie Guevara, an engineer at the company, tweeted at Mr. Musk after his visit to the office.\par \par \uc2 ''Was it fun to look at the faces of the people you said you'd be laying off?'' she wrote. The post was quickly seized upon by Musk's fans, who called for her to be fired.\par \par \uc2 Cryptocurrency enthusiasts have been heartened by Elon Musk's discussion of integration and of digital wallets. (PHOTOGRAPH BY ODD ANDERSEN/AGENCE FRANCE-PRESSE -- GETTY IMAGES) (B5) This article appeared in print on page B1, B5. \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020221031eiat0001k\par }\p