\par\par \uc2 THE SHIFT\par \uc2 Business/Financial Desk; SECTB\par \b \uc2 What \uc2 Twitter\uc2  May Become With Musk At the Helm\b0\par\par\uc2 By Kevin Roose \par \uc2 1,963 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 October 2022\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2022 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 His deal to buy the company is back on. Here are six predictions about \uc2 Twitter\uc2  under Musk's control, if it happens.\par \par \uc2 Buckle up.\par \par \uc2 Elon Musk\uc2 , who for months has been strenuously trying to back out of a deal to buy \uc2 Twitter\uc2  for $44 billion, now appears ready to buy the company after all. In a surprise letter to \uc2 Twitter\uc2  on Monday night, Mr. Musk offered to take \uc2 Twitter\uc2  private at his originally proposed price -- $54.20 per share -- marking a possible end to one of the most dramatic legal feuds in Silicon Valley history.\par \par \uc2 It's worth noting that the deal could still fall apart -- Mr. Musk is famously subject to 11th-hour mood shifts -- but the most likely outcome now is that the world's richest man will in fact become \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's new owner, possibly as soon as this week.\par \par \uc2 Much is unknown about what Mr. Musk will do with \uc2 Twitter\uc2  if he acquires it. The mercurial billionaire has made only the vaguest of public statements about his plans for the company and its products.\par \par \uc2 But we now know, thanks in part to a bevy of text messages released as part of the protracted legal battle, that it will be nothing like business as usual. And there are at least six predictions I feel confident making, if the deal does in fact close.\par \par \uc2 He's going to clean house, starting with firing \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's chief executive, \uc2 Parag Agrawal\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 A juicy set of text messages between Mr. Musk and his friends and business associates emerged last week, as part of the legal battle. In them, Mr. Musk made clear that he was unhappy with \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's current leadership -- in particular with \uc2 Parag Agrawal\uc2 , the chief executive, who took over last year from \uc2 Jack Dorsey\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The texts revealed that Mr. Agrawal had initially sought to work constructively with Mr. Musk, and that the two even had a friendly dinner near San Jose, Calif., in March. But the men eventually clashed. Mr. Agrawal, at one point, told Mr. Musk via text message that his habit of tweeting things like ''Is \uc2 Twitter\uc2  dying?'' was ''not helping me make \uc2 Twitter\uc2  better.''\par \par \uc2 ''What did you get done this week?'' Mr. Musk shot back. ''This is a waste of time.''\par \par \uc2 From reading Mr. Musk's texts, it's clear he believes that \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's leadership is weak and ineffective, and lacks the ability to carry out his vision for the company. If Mr. Agrawal doesn't immediately resign once the deal is complete, I'd expect Mr. Musk to fire him on Day 1 and name himself or a close ally as a replacement.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Musk has also expressed displeasure with other \uc2 Twitter\uc2  executives, and it's hard to see how he could fire Mr. Agrawal without also clearing out most or all of the company's top leadership and installing his own slate of loyalists.\par \par \uc2 Employees will revolt.\par \par \uc2 Another easy prediction to make about Mr. Musk's takeover is that it will generate enormous backlash among \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's rank-and-file employees.\par \par \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , more so than other social media platforms, has a vocally progressive work force and many employees who are deeply invested in the company's mission of promoting ''healthy conversation.'' Those employees may believe -- for good reason! -- that under Mr. Musk's leadership, \uc2 Twitter\uc2  will abandon many of the projects they care about in areas like trust and safety. Or they may simply not want to deal with the drama and tumult of a Musk regime, and start looking for jobs elsewhere.\par \par \uc2 Some employees have already quit, anticipating a Musk takeover. And it's safe to bet that many more will follow if the deal actually closes.\par \par \uc2 It's worth noting that in his texts with Mr. Musk, Mr. Agrawal claimed that a ''large silent majority'' of \uc2 Twitter\uc2  employees supported Mr. Musk's vision. But virtually every \uc2 Twitter\uc2  employee I've spoken to in the last six months has told me that he or she plans to leave if Mr. Musk takes over.\par \par \uc2 It's also worth noting that Mr. Musk may not mind if thousands of \uc2 Twitter\uc2  employees show themselves the door. He has implied that the company's staff is bloated, and now that he needs to justify a $44 billion price tag, an exodus of unhappy employees might be the kind of savings he's looking for.\par \par \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2  will return to \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , along with a swarm of other right-wing culture warriors.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Musk, who has framed his bid for \uc2 Twitter\uc2  as an attempt to preserve free speech on the platform, has long said that, if successful, he would allow former President \uc2 Donald J. Trump\uc2  to reclaim his \uc2 Twitter\uc2  account, which was permanently suspended last year after the Jan. 6 insurrection at the Capitol.\par \par \uc2 That will happen almost immediately, I predict. (And, yes, Mr. Trump will come back to \uc2 Twitter\uc2  if he's invited, no matter how much fun he's having on Truth Social.)\par \par \uc2 But Mr. Musk's ''replatforming'' will extend far beyond the former president. A host of right-wing culture warriors could come back to the service with Mr. Musk's blessing, including those who were barred for expressing hateful views, spreading false conspiracy theories and harassing other users. (In his text messages, Mr. Musk told Mr. Agrawal that he wanted to reverse all permanent \uc2 Twitter\uc2  bans ''except for spam accounts and those that explicitly advocate violence.'')\par \par \uc2 Mr. Musk, who styles himself a centrist but often crusades against the ''woke left,'' has made no secret of his plans to make \uc2 Twitter\uc2  a friendlier platform for right-wing voices. He has expressed support for The Babylon Bee, a conservative satire site whose \uc2 Twitter\uc2  account was suspended after it published a transphobic humor piece about a Biden administration official. And Representative \uc2 Marjorie Taylor Greene\uc2 , whose personal \uc2 Twitter\uc2  account was suspended this year for repeatedly sharing misinformation about Covid-19 vaccines, has urged Mr. Musk to reinstate her along with other right-wing commentators, including Alex Jones, the founder of Infowars.\par \par \uc2 Along with one-off reversals of high-profile bans, I'd also expect that Mr. Musk would tear up \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's existing rules and rewrite new ones, and that he might dismantle \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's content-policy and trust-and-safety teams, which are responsible for enforcing the platform's rules as they currently exist. (That is, if those teams don't quit en masse first.)\par \par \uc2 He might even name his own set of free-speech absolutists. One friend of Mr. Musk's suggested that he install someone like \uc2 Blake Masters\uc2 , the Republican Senate candidate from Arizona, as \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's head of enforcement, according to the trove of text messages released during the court battle. (Mr. Musk did not respond to the suggestion.)\par \par \uc2 It probably won't change the midterms, but 2024 could be the Elon Election.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Musk's takeover could happen before next month's midterm elections. And if it does, there could still be time for him to make decisions, like allowing Mr. Trump back on the platform or loosening restrictions on political ads, that could reshape the conversation about some races.\par \par \uc2 But Mr. Musk -- who, let's not forget, runs several other companies -- will have his hands full between now and November. And I don't think that, with only a month left until the elections, there will be a straight line from Mr. Musk's takeover to, say, a Republican sweep of close House and Senate races.\par \par \uc2 The 2024 election, though, will be a different story. By then, if the deal is consummated, Mr. Musk will have been able to more fully mold \uc2 Twitter\uc2  in his own image. The platform could look radically different by then -- more right-wing trolls, fewer guardrails against misinformation and extremism -- or it could be largely the same. But Mr. Musk will be firmly in charge, and if \uc2 Twitter\uc2  still plays anywhere near the role in American political and media culture that it does today, he will emerge as a central, polarizing figure in the 2024 election cycle.\par \par \uc2 Republicans are, for obvious reasons, excited about Mr. Musk's taking over. But the ultimate political consequences of his ownership are harder to predict. It's theoretically possible -- though, I concede, probably unlikely -- that Mr. Musk's owning \uc2 Twitter\uc2  could be good for Democrats in 2022 and 2024, if it allows more Republican politicians to stake out extreme positions on \uc2 Twitter\uc2  that end up backfiring on them at the ballot box.\par \par \uc2 But whatever moves Mr. Musk makes before 2024, it's a good bet that they will be closely scrutinized for signs that he is putting his thumb on the scale.\par \par \uc2 Twitter\uc2  will kill unpopular features, go after bots and introduce new subscription products.\par \par \uc2 Some of the most revealing exchanges in Mr. Musk's trove of text messages were about his thoughts on \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's products.\par \par \uc2 In particular, Mr. Musk was dismissive of Twitter Blue, the company's subscription-based product that gives users access to premium features like ad-free articles and an undo button for tweets. Perhaps surprisingly, given his love of cryptocurrency, Mr. Musk also appeared skeptical of proposals to rebuild \uc2 Twitter\uc2  on a decentralized \uc2 blockchain\uc2 , saying that ''\uc2 blockchain\uc2 Twitter\uc2  won't work.''\par \par \uc2 Based on his statements, and pitches he made to investors this summer while trying to pull a deal together, I'd expect Mr. Musk to make several changes to \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's products early on. First, he will move to shut down many of \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's noncore features -- including some of those in Twitter Blue, but also any other features that don't generate much revenue for the company. He will try to rid the site of spam bots, a problem that he has long singled out as one of the worst parts of \uc2 Twitter\uc2 . (And which formed the basis of his spurious attempt to get out of the \uc2 Twitter\uc2  deal, back before he decided to buy it again.)\par \par \uc2 Mr. Musk will also try to shift \uc2 Twitter\uc2  away from advertising revenue and toward other moneymaking opportunities -- including payments features, data-licensing agreements and a mysterious new subscription product, which he has called only X, and which he has claimed will have 104 million paying users by 2028.\par \par \uc2 Musk will remain the center of attention.\par \par \uc2 Perhaps the easiest prediction to make about Mr. Musk's \uc2 Twitter\uc2  takeover is that it will make him an even bigger celebrity.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Musk is, of course, already one of the most well known people in the world. But until now, his power has largely been a function of his extreme wealth and the size of his online following. He could get in flame wars, make crude jokes about senators or threaten to move his companies out of California, and all of this mattered a great deal to the people involved -- but it was all ultimately soft power that was contingent on \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's willingness to let him keep throwing bombs at his 108 million followers, and the public's willingness to keep paying attention.\par \par \uc2 Owning \uc2 Twitter\uc2  is different. If the deal closes, Mr. Musk will have direct control over one of the world's largest megaphones, and will be able to use it entirely as he sees fit -- whether that's to turn it into a lawless free-for-all, take revenge on his political enemies, promote his own business ventures or do something else entirely. And given Mr. Musk's penchant for seizing the spotlight, we can expect that whatever he chooses to do with \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , it won't be boring.\par \par \uc2 There was already no escaping Mr. Musk. Now, looking away will be truly impossible.\par \par \uc2 (PHOTOGRAPH BY JONATHAN NEWTON/THE WASHINGTON POST VIA GETTY IMAGES) (B5) \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020221005eia50005e\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw284\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4260\pichgoal600
