\par\par \uc2 Business/Financial Desk; SECTB\par \b \uc2 Treasury Bans Crypto Platform Over Money Laundering\b0\par\par\uc2 By David Yaffe-Bellany \par \uc2 527 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 August 2022\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2022 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 The crackdown was the government's latest effort to rein in the crypto industry.\par \par \uc2 The Treasury Department on Monday prohibited Americans from using the cryptocurrency platform Tornado Cash, saying the service has helped criminals launder more than $7 billion of virtual currencies.\par \par \uc2 The crackdown was the \uc2 U.S. government\uc2 's latest effort to rein in the crypto industry, as lawmakers and regulators grow increasingly concerned over the volatility of virtual currencies and their role in facilitating hacking and other crimes. Calling the platform a ''threat to U.S. national security,'' the Treasury Department placed Tornado Cash on a blacklist of entities, making it illegal for Americans to send or receive money using the service.\par \par \uc2 ''Despite public assurances otherwise, Tornado Cash has repeatedly failed to impose effective controls designed to stop it from laundering funds for malicious cyber actors,'' Brian Nelson, the under secretary for terrorism and financial intelligence, said in a statement.\par \par \uc2 Criminals have long used virtual currencies to transact anonymously, exchanging digital coins for drugs or other illicit wares. But the anonymity of crypto doesn't provide blanket security: Crypto transactions are recorded on publicly viewable ledgers called blockchains, allowing law enforcement officials to follow the money.\par \par \uc2 Platforms like Tornado Cash are designed to make that kind of tracking harder. These crypto ''mixers'' receive multiple streams of transactions, then combine them to obscure the origin and destination of the funds. According to the Treasury Department, Tornado Cash was used to launder more than $455 million in crypto stolen this year by North Korean-backed hackers called the Lazarus Group.\par \par \uc2 A message to Tornado Cash's official \uc2 Twitter\uc2  account was not returned. Roman Semenov, one of the company's three founders, did not respond to a request for comment.\par \par \uc2 Since its launch in 2019, Tornado Cash has risen to prominence largely because \uc2 blockchain\uc2  records show that hackers have used it to move stolen cryptocurrencies. In interviews, Mr. Semenov has defended the service, saying the software protects the privacy of legitimate crypto traders who could be targeted by kidnappers or thieves.\par \par \uc2 In a statement, the crypto advocacy group Coin Center criticized the Treasury Department's announcement, arguing that Tornado Cash is a neutral platform ''that can be put to good or bad uses like any other technology.''\par \par \uc2 ''It is not any specific bad actor who is being sanctioned,'' the statement said. ''Instead it is all Americans who may wish to use this automated tool in order to protect their own privacy while transacting online.''\par \par \uc2 As the market for digital currencies has grown, the federal government has increasingly cracked down on crypto companies, which are lightly regulated. Tether, a stablecoin company, was fined last year by the \uc2 Commodity Futures Trading Commission\uc2  for misstatements about its reserves, while the Justice Department brought insider-trading charges last month against a former employee of \uc2 Coinbase\uc2 , the largest U.S. crypto exchange.\par \par \uc2 The cryptocurrency exchange \uc2 Kraken\uc2  is also under investigation by the Treasury Department for possible violations of U.S. sanctions.\par \par \uc2  records show how Tornado Cash was used to move stolen crypto. (PHOTOGRAPH BY LUKE MACGREGOR/BLOOMBERG) \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020220809ei890004h\par }\page {\par\f