\par\par \uc2 Business/Financial Desk; SECTB\par \b \uc2 People Flock to South Korean Crypto Event Despite Upheaval in the Sector\b0\par\par\uc2 By Jin Yu Young \par \uc2 466 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 August 2022\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2022 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Falling prices and upheaval in the industry do not appear to have curbed Koreans' appetite for crypto, \uc2 blockchain\uc2  and all things web3.\par \par \uc2 When the South Korean cryptocurrencies Luna and TerraUSD collapsed in May, their failures contributed to a $300 billion loss across the crypto economy; public outcries for Do Kwon, the cryptocurrencies' creator, to go to jail; and multiple investigations. But that, and a broader ''crypto winter'' dragging down prices across the industry, do not appear to have curbed South Korea's appetite for all things web3.\par \par \uc2 Korea \uc2 Blockchain\uc2  Week opened this weekend with more than 7,000 people registered to attend and over 120 speakers on the lineup. According to the event's chief executive officer, Jeon Seon-ik, this year's event was one of the largest of its kind in Asia, if not the world.\par \par \uc2 One of the keynote speakers, Seo Sang-min, who runs the Klaytn Foundation, a prominent South Korean \uc2 blockchain\uc2  company, attributed the event's popularity to a South Korean penchant for tech.\par \par \uc2 ''Despite the Luna-Terra crash, the nation is big on crypto and is one of the tech centers of the world,'' he said in an interview.\par \par \uc2 Vitalik Buterin\uc2 , a co-founder and the chief scientist at Ethereum, the system that runs the world's second-largest cryptocurrency after Bitcoin, also gave a keynote speech. He emphasized the need to make crypto transactions more affordable for a wider range of users and promoting the benefits of a decentralized financial system.\par \par \uc2 Cryptocurrency first surged in South Korea in 2017 after the country's largest conglomerate, \uc2 Samsung\uc2 , announced that it would find a corporate use for Ethereum. \uc2 Samsung SDS\uc2  was the first Korean enterprise to join the \uc2 Enterprise Ethereum Alliance\uc2 , which started in San Francisco that year to facilitate business transactions.\par \par \uc2 Since then, South Korea's crypto market has grown to be one of the largest in the world. The country's crypto assets grew to 55 trillion won at the end of last year, worth about $46 billion at the time, with more than 15 million registered users of trading platforms, according to the country's Financial Services Commission. A few years ago, the South Korean government adopted a more wary stance on cryptocurrencies, and even considered banning them. More recently, though, the government has moved to regulate the industry.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Seo believes that the government's shift in approach is an acknowledgment of the industry's potential. ''The metaverse and web3 have potential to be more than a means of investment, create new jobs and solve real-world problems,'' he said.\par \par \uc2 Outside a cryptocurrency exchange in Seoul. (PHOTOGRAPH BY Kim Hong-Ji/Reuters FOR THE NEW YORK TIMES) \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020220809ei890004d\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw284\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4260\pichgoal600
