\par\par \uc2 Business/Financial Desk; SECTB\par \b \uc2 Ex-\uc2 Coinbase\uc2  Worker Among 3 Charged With Insider Trading of Crypto\b0\par\par\uc2 By Matthew Goldstein and David Yaffe-Bellany \par \uc2 967 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 July 2022\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2022 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 The case is the first time criminal insider-trading charges have been filed that involve cryptocurrency assets, a U.S. attorney said.\par \par \uc2 Federal authorities filed criminal and civil charges against a former \uc2 Coinbase\uc2  employee and two other men in an insider trading case involving confidential information about cryptocurrency assets that were about to be posted on \uc2 Coinbase\uc2 's exchange, according to charging documents filed on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 The three men were involved in trades over 10 months using information about 14 listings on \uc2 Coinbase\uc2  that generated about $1.5 million in illegal profits, according to federal prosecutors in Manhattan. The men were charged criminally with three counts of wire fraud and conspiracy to commit wire fraud.\par \par \uc2 The case is the first time the authorities have filed criminal insider-trading charges involving cryptocurrency assets, said \uc2 Damian Williams\uc2 , the U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York.\par \par \uc2 The prosecutors, as well as the \uc2 Securities and Exchange Commission\uc2  in civil charging documents, said Ishan Wahi, who at the time was part of a \uc2 Coinbase\uc2  team that listed assets on the exchange, passed on confidential information about when some cryptocurrency assets would be listed to his brother, Nikhil Wahi, and his brother's friend Sammer Ramani.\par \par \uc2 Nikhil Wahi and Mr. Ramani used that information to buy the assets before \uc2 Coinbase\uc2  announced they'd be listed, the authorities said. After the announcement, the men sold the assets for a profit.\par \par \uc2 The alleged scheme came to light after \uc2 Coinbase\uc2  began an internal investigation in April in response to a post on \uc2 Twitter\uc2  about unusual trading.\par \par \uc2 Ishan Wahi booked a flight to India just before the company was to interview him in the investigation. The authorities said he had tipped off his brother and his brother's friend about the interview as well. Mr. Wahi and his brother were arrested on Thursday morning in Seattle. Mr. Ramani remained at large, the authorities said.\par \par \uc2 Lawyers for Ishan Wahi said their client ''is innocent of all wrongdoing and intends to defend himself vigorously against these charges.'' A lawyer for his brother did not immediately respond to a request for comment. Mr. Ramani couldn't immediately be reached for comment. The S.E.C. said that Mr. Ramani is a Houston resident but that it believed he was in India.\par \par \uc2 The charges suggest that federal authorities are prepared to crack down on illicit trading in the world of digital assets in much the same way they have pursued such crimes in the stock, bond and commodity markets.\par \par \uc2 ''Our message with these charges is clear: Fraud is fraud is fraud, whether it occurs on the \uc2 blockchain\uc2  or on Wall Street,'' Mr. Williams, the U.S. attorney, said.\par \par \uc2 The S.E.C. said the cryptocurrency assets listed on \uc2 Coinbase\uc2 's exchange are considered securities and, therefore, can be regulated like stocks or bonds -- a stance that many in the digital currency world have objected to.\par \par \uc2 Last month, federal prosecutors brought an insider trading case involving the use of confidential information to purchase another kind of digital assets, nonfungible tokens, or NFTs. In that case, the authorities charged a former employee of an NFT marketplace with misappropriating confidential information about the timing of public listings for the digital tokens.\par \par \uc2 The S.E.C. did not file any enforcement action in the insider trading case involving NFTs.\par \par \uc2 The two criminal cases ''are just the beginning of the D.O.J.'s crackdown on insider trading in the crypto space,'' said Ian McGinley, a former Justice Department prosecutor. ''Both of these cases are for relatively small amounts, but D.O.J. brought them to send a message: They are watching.''\par \par \uc2 In a post on \uc2 Coinbase\uc2 's website, the company's chief executive, \uc2 Brian Armstrong\uc2 , said \uc2 Coinbase\uc2  had turned over information about the three men to the Justice Department and had ended Mr. Wahi's employment. ''We have zero tolerance for this kind of misconduct and will not hesitate to take action against any employee when we find wrongdoing,'' he wrote.\par \par \uc2 But Mr. Armstrong took issue in the post with the S.E.C.'s decision to file civil securities fraud charges. He wrote that the assets on \uc2 Coinbase\uc2 's exchange are not securities and noted that federal prosecutors had not charged the men with securities fraud.\par \par \uc2 The move by the S.E.C. prompted a rare rebuke from an official with another regulator. Caroline D. Pham, a commissioner with the \uc2 Commodity Futures Trading Commission\uc2 , wrote on \uc2 Twitter\uc2  that the S.E.C.'s complaint ''was a striking example of 'regulation by enforcement.''' Ms. Pham, who was sworn in as a commissioner in April after being nominated by President Biden, said the S.E.C.'s decision to pursue securities fraud charges in this case had broader ramifications for the crypto industry and the appropriate regulatory framework.\par \par \uc2 In response, an S.E.C. official said, ''The complaint speaks for itself.''\par \par \uc2 In an interview, \uc2 Paul Grewal\uc2 , \uc2 Coinbase\uc2 's chief legal officer, said the company had a team of 50 investigators, including former federal prosecutors, who monitored suspicious activity on the platform. ''These signals that we're looking for are extremely faint in a very loud, complicated system,'' he said.\par \par \uc2 The impetus for the investigation into Mr. Wahi was a tweet from an account under the name Cobie that used public transaction records to identify the suspicious trading.\par \par \uc2 When the charges were filed on Thursday, the account -- which is reportedly run by the crypto influencer Jordan Fish -- struck a modest tone.\par \par \uc2 ''Confusing that people actually read tweets from this twitter account in the real world and then do stuff about them,'' Cobie wrote.\par \par \uc2 (PHOTOGRAPH BY Shannon Stapleton/Reuters FOR THE NEW YORK TIMES) \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020220722ei7m00048\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw284\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4260\pichgoal600
