\par\par \uc2 Style Desk; SECTD\par \b \uc2 Desert Merriment Knows No Bounds\b0\par\par\uc2 By Andr\u233\'00\'E9 Wheeler \par \uc2 1,615 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 May 2022\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2022 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 A young man sporting elf ears and a pink beard danced shirtless to trance music. A crowd of people sipped Liquid Death, a new water brand marketed at festivals, as they shimmied and swayed, striking up conversations with strangers. Bystanders sat on grassy hills for a bird's-eye view, taking in the colorful scene with intrigue. In a corner, a woman tested out a ''sensory experience'' chair, wearing a virtual-reality headset as her high-tech chair vibrated vigorously. Candy-scented clouds traveled from vape to mouth to air.\par \par \uc2 Welcome to Robot Heart. These parties, organized by the Robot Heart Foundation, which describes itself as a ''collective of dreamers and doers,'' typically lean toward a communal, countercultural brand of fun, and are normally held in Nevada's Black Rock Desert during Burning Man festivals.\par \par \uc2 On this occasion, however, the foundation was celebrating its inaugural event in New York City, billed as Fare Forward, at Wollman Rink in Central Park. The merriment was a tad more controlled in its new urban environs. Police officers monitored the scene, and all of the action began at 2 p.m. on a Saturday and Sunday and ended promptly at 10 p.m. -- an acceptable bedtime.\par \par \uc2 This two-day affair, on April 30 and May 1, was a return to glory, in a sense. The pandemic put a hard pause on Robot Heart, which debuted in 2008, just as it did the much-larger Burning Man festival. The loss was acutely felt among ''Burners'' (passionate festival devotees).\par \par \uc2 This gathering has grown into a refuge for a motley crowd that includes creative nomads, Bushwick art performers and Silicon Valley tech heads. At each event, a 1972 ''Mad Max''-esque Bristol bus outfitted with speakers, called the ''Robot Heart Art Bus,'' blasts sets by renowned D.J.s.\par \par \uc2 The sun-soaked reprieves from the outside world were founded and led by George Mueller, known as ''Geo,'' who died unexpectedly last year from a cerebral aneurysm. This month's festival was the first Robot Heart event thrown since his death, and attendees let loose in part to honor him.\par \par \uc2 A democratic, egalitarian spirt reigned on the dance floor. Bodies were pressed close together as strangers connected. Occasionally, someone would spot an old friend they had met at Burning Man and shout hello. When nightfall arrived, colorful LED lights glided over the crowd and articles of clothing were strewn throughout the grounds. Kisses were exchanged here and there.\par \par \uc2 And there was plenty to do in the V.I.P. section, accessible with tickets. Guests ordered giant plates of sushi (which ranged from $200 to $1,500). A tent for meditation and tarot card readings was pitched.\par \par \uc2 This Robot Heart may not have embodied the full-fledged festival experience many of the attendees desperately craved. That will come this summer, when Burning Man makes its long-awaited return to Black Rock. But, after a two-year pause on festival life, the weekend served an important purpose that mirrors much of this year: inching back to normal.\par \par \uc2 Nana Meriwether\par \par \uc2 Age: 36\par \par \uc2 From: Washington, D.C., and New York City\par \par \uc2 I heard you're a pageant star.\par \par \uc2 I won Miss USA many years ago.\par \par \uc2 Congrats. What do you do now?\par \par \uc2 I work in \uc2 blockchain\uc2  at a firm that was founded by the guy behind Ethereum.\par \par \uc2 What brings you out here today?\par \par \uc2 Today is a celebration of life. Robot Heart is one of the most famous camps at Burning Man. If you go to Burning Man, you know Robot Heart.\par \par \uc2 How many times have you been to Burning Man?\par \par \uc2 This will be my fifth year. But my first year I hitchhiked from the airport, found a plot of land, pitched a tent and lived out in the desert for a week by myself.\par \par \uc2 Did you make friends?\par \par \uc2 Yes, absolutely. It's really a journey for yourself, whether you're in a camp or not. It completely changed my life.\par \par \uc2 What did you learn from that experience?\par \par \uc2 You really learn what you need to learn at that specific moment. At that time, I was really dealing with loneliness. And being alone. So I was alone for an entire week! I learned to finally be OK with being by myself. Now I've manifested a huge community here and other places.\par \par \uc2 Do you still feel lonely?\par \par \uc2 No. I've found myself. And the catalyst was Burning Man.\par \par \uc2 Tara Solomon\par \par \uc2 Age: 63\par \par \uc2 Occupation: Writer and entrepreneur\par \par \uc2 From: Miami Beach, Fla.\par \par \uc2 Tell me about your outfit.\par \par \uc2 Today's inspo was Walter Mercado meets Endora from ''Bewitched.'' Which is my everyday drag. This is not festival wear -- I look like this every day. I have never packed for a trip faster and with more joy.\par \par \uc2 Where are some of the pieces from?\par \par \uc2 The bag and glasses are Gucci. The ostrich jacket is Zac Posen. The ring is Alexander McQueen. Suede cowboy boots that my cousin bought for me in Texas. Vintage tights. Vintage Napier pendant necklace, probably from the mid-70s. Tom Ford Beauty makeup.\par \par \uc2 Is it fair to assume you're a big fan of vintage clothing?\par \par \uc2 Yes. I've maxed out my saved searches on \uc2 eBay\uc2 . They won't let me put anymore!\par \par \uc2 What's the number on that?\par \par \uc2 Something like 150, I think.\par \par \uc2 What's the power of fashion for you?\par \par \uc2 It's about expressing yourself. But in order to express yourself, you have to know yourself. And in order to know yourself, you have to love yourself. I know myself very well.\par \par \uc2 Manchildblack and Monstah Black\par \par \uc2 Ages: 41 and 45\par \par \uc2 Occupation: Musicians who perform as the Illustrious Blacks.\par \par \uc2 Tell me about your outfits.\par \par \uc2 Manchildblack: These are our after-show ones, actually. We were performing today and had a whole different ensemble. But this is more of our casual after-performance look. And we're bringing you purity with the white.\par \par \uc2 Were your outfits matching onstage too?\par \par \uc2 Manchildblack: Yes. They were multicolored.\par \par \uc2 Monstah: And tight!\par \par \uc2 Where are you based?\par \par \uc2 Manchildblack: Planet Brooklyn. We are currently in the Republic of Bed-Stuy. However we are going to be traveling to the magical land of Flatbush very soon.\par \par \uc2 Tell me about your musical style.\par \par \uc2 Manchildblack: We call ourselves the ''afro-electro-disco space punks.''\par \par \uc2 Monstah: It ranges from house funk, disco and techno, a little bit of punk thrown in there.\par \par \uc2 What are some shows coming up that you're excited to perform at?\par \par \uc2 Manchildblack: Lisbon, Portugal! We're going to celebrate Pride there with them.\par \par \uc2 Leiti Hsu, a.k.a. 'the Dining Dominatrix'\par \par \uc2 Age: 36\par \par \uc2 What's the meaning behind ''Dining Dominatrix''?\par \par \uc2 I'm all about spoiling you with food, love, permission and pleasure.\par \par \uc2 Tell me about your outfit.\par \par \uc2 If you took the word ''compersion'' -- which is all about loving other people having love and pleasure -- and put it into a kaleidoscope, and then took the color hot pink. Ta-da! It's an explosion of pleasure.\par \par \uc2 Andy and Keke Levy\par \par \uc2 Ages: 60 and 44\par \par \uc2 What do you do?\par \par \uc2 Andy: I'm a surgeon.\par \par \uc2 Tell me about your outfits.\par \par \uc2 Andy: It's from our costume closet. Which is bigger than our regular closet!\par \par \uc2 Keke: I wanted something shimmery. Something that shimmers in the sun while I dance.\par \par \uc2 What brings you here today?\par \par \uc2 Andy: We go way back with these folks. We've been going to Burning Man for over 10 years. It's like a family reunion for us. Throughout the pandemic and everything, we haven't been able to see our friends. You know, people who go to Burning Man love masks, but we suck at social distancing. We like to hug.\par \par \uc2 Do festivals play a big role in your marriage?\par \par \uc2 Andy: Not festivals in general. It's more so certain festivals, certain events. A lot of our friends like to get dressed up. It's more great parties with wonderful people we happen to meet in the desert.\par \par \uc2 Olga Rakhova\par \par \uc2 Age: ''Ageless''\par \par \uc2 Occupation: Designer\par \par \uc2 OK, tell me about the horse prop you're carrying.\par \par \uc2 Apparently my genetic female line, according to \uc2 23andMe\uc2 , came from a group in Africa that settled 2,000 years ago and took care of horses. So maybe that's why I was drawn to it. I have horses in many colors and I match them to my outfit. But I only take them out to places where they will be accepted, like here.\par \par \uc2 Does he have a name?\par \par \uc2 Fernando.\par \par \uc2 How long did it take to get ready?\par \par \uc2 Not long. I had to dress the horse and some of my friends too.\par \par \uc2 Gaby Endo\par \par \uc2 Age: 34\par \par \uc2 What do you do?\par \par \uc2 I have a costume shop here in New York City. It's where I got this costume from.\par \par \uc2 What's it called?\par \par \uc2 Harmonia NY.\par \par \uc2 Tell me about your outfit.\par \par \uc2 I'm telling a story about happiness, fluidity and celebrating the cause of life, which is why we're all here today. We're here to be happy, to express ourselves. This outfit is spring awakening.\par \par \uc2 Do you go to Burning Man and other festivals a lot?\par \par \uc2 Yes, I've gone for five years. I am also a D.J. I'm playing the after-party.\par \par \uc2 Have you made any new friends today?\par \par \uc2 I actually know a lot of people here from Burning Man. So it's been a lot of catching up. I also have a baby, so I was busy at home with him before this. Now the babysitter's watching him.\par \par \uc2 An inflatable mushroom shaded some festivalgoers at Robot Heart's Fare Forward event at Wollman Rink in Central Park on April 30. (PHOTOGRAPHS BY CALLA KESSLER FOR THE NEW YORK TIMES) \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020220519ei5c00004\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw284\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4260\pichgoal600
