\par\par \uc2 Business/Financial Desk; SECTB\par \b \uc2 Musk Adds Investors To Fund \uc2 Twitter\uc2  Deal\b0\par\par\uc2 By Lauren Hirsch, Anupreeta Das, Erin Griffith and Mike Isaac \par \uc2 1,467 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 May 2022\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2022 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 The filing lists a number of investment firms and other backers who will contribute $7 billion to the deal.\par \par \uc2 In numerous conversations over the last several days, \uc2 Elon Musk\uc2  began making promises about what he could do with \uc2 Twitter\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Mr. Musk, the world's richest man, told potential investors that he could double the number of users on the platform to more than half a billion by 2025, four people briefed on the conversations said. Not only that, he said, he could more than double \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's revenue by that date and bring tens of millions of paying subscribers to the service, two of the people said.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Musk added that investors would make a handsome return if they bought into his pitch. And he told them that he would take charge of \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , at least for a time, as its chief executive.\par \par \uc2 Investors bought in. On Thursday, Mr. Musk revealed that he had raised around $7 billion from 18 entities to help fund his blockbuster $44 billion acquisition of \uc2 Twitter\uc2 . The investors were a mix of Mr. Musk's Silicon Valley friends -- including venture capital firms such as \uc2 Andreessen Horowitz\uc2  and tech moguls like \uc2 Larry Ellison\uc2  -- as well as cryptocurrency companies, family offices, sovereign wealth funds, property firms and mutual-fund companies.\par \par \uc2 While many traditional private equity firms passed on participating because of concerns over Mr. Musk's business plans for \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , Silicon Valley investors and others clamored to join the financing, people with knowledge of the situation said. The overriding reason was their faith in Mr. Musk, they said.\par \par \uc2 ''We believe in Elon's brilliance to finally make it what it was meant to be,'' \uc2 Ben Horowitz\uc2 , a founder of \uc2 Andreessen Horowitz\uc2 , tweeted about Mr. Musk's takeover of \uc2 Twitter\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Mr. Horowitz, whose firm contributed $400 million, added that Mr. Musk was ''perhaps the only person in the world who has the courage, brilliance, and skills to fix'' \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's issues and ''build the public square that we all hoped for and deserve.''\par \par \uc2 The new funding commitments were a sign that Mr. Musk, who leads the electric carmaker \uc2 Tesla\uc2  and the rocket company \uc2 SpaceX\uc2 , was continuing to figure out his plans for \uc2 Twitter\uc2  after striking a deal 10 days ago to buy the company. When the 50-year-old announced his intention to take over \uc2 Twitter\uc2  last month, he appeared far from prepared. He had no financing lined up, did not say who might lead the company and did not articulate how it might make money.\par \par \uc2 Instead, Mr. Musk spoke in general terms. He said he planned to take \uc2 Twitter\uc2  private so he could work on improving the product away from the public eye. He also said he wanted to promote more free speech on the platform.\par \par \uc2 The lack of a comprehensive plan was typical for Mr. Musk, who often acts on impulse and figures out the details later. That leads to plenty of risks and means investors often have to take a big leap to invest with him.\par \par \uc2 Even so, Mr. Musk's seat-of-the-pants methods have led to tremendous successes, including making \uc2 Tesla\uc2  the world's most valuable automaker and pioneering the privatization of space launches with \uc2 SpaceX\uc2 . That record helped draw the new investors -- which also include \uc2 Binance\uc2 , the cryptocurrency exchange, and \uc2 Qatar Holding\uc2 , a sovereign wealth fund -- to the \uc2 Twitter\uc2  deal, investors said.\par \par \uc2 ''Many more people have made money betting on Elon than against him,'' said \uc2 Mark Pincus\uc2 , who founded the social gaming company \uc2 Zynga\uc2  and knows Mr. Musk.\par \par \uc2 Many of the new investors also shared Mr. Musk's views or interests. Just like the billionaire, for example, \uc2 Marc Andreessen\uc2 , a founder of \uc2 Andreessen Horowitz\uc2 , is a free-speech enthusiast and a backer of crypto technologies.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Musk said in a securities filing on Thursday that he was continuing to talk with other investors, including \uc2 Jack Dorsey\uc2 , \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's co-founder. The two men have discussed rolling over Mr. Dorsey's stake in the company so he would remain an investor once Mr. Musk took over, Mr. Musk said. He is also reviewing requests from other investors and could announce additional capital commitments in coming weeks, one person briefed on the matter said.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Musk and a spokeswoman for Mr. Dorsey did not respond to requests for comment.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Musk's original financing package for \uc2 Twitter\uc2  included $13 billion in loans from seven banks, $21 billion of his own cash and a $12.5 billion loan against his shares in \uc2 Tesla\uc2 . With the new equity commitments, Mr. Musk said he was reducing the size of the loan against his \uc2 Tesla\uc2  shares to $6.25 billion. He has not outlined the sources of the $21 billion in cash for the deal.\par \par \uc2 The new funds could give investors more confidence that Mr. Musk's deal for \uc2 Twitter\uc2  will close. Some investors had bet against that likelihood, given Mr. Musk's unpredictable nature and how much capital he may personally be on the hook for. The deal is not set to close for three to six months. Mr. Musk must pay a $1 billion breakup fee if his financing falls apart.\par \par \uc2 ''This was a smart financial and strategic move by Musk that will be well received across the board,'' said \uc2 Daniel Ives\uc2 , a managing director and analyst at the investment firm \uc2 Wedbush\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Mr. Musk's bankers at \uc2 Morgan Stanley\uc2  reached out to some investors late last week, said one person who heard the pitch. In meetings, Mr. Musk criticized \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's current state and pitched his vision for improving the company's product and business model, the person said.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Musk told investors that he was highly confident he could double or triple their money. He added that while a return of five to 10 times would be a challenge, it was possible if all went well. The billionaire also promised to devote time and energy to \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , the person said.\par \par \uc2 The projected numbers included \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's annual revenue exceeding $13 billion and its earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization -- a measure of profitability -- potentially hitting $6 billion by 2025, two people who viewed the numbers said.\par \par \uc2 Investors were given a few days to make a decision. Some balked at the speed and lack of detail on governance issues, including voting rights, information rights and the makeup of \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's board of directors under Mr. Musk's stewardship, one person said. The $44 billion that Mr. Musk is paying for \uc2 Twitter\uc2  was also a sticking point, given the company's inconsistent profits, the person said.\par \par \uc2 Morgan Stanley\uc2  declined to comment.\par \par \uc2 Some investors didn't wait for Mr. Musk to reach out to them. \uc2 Binance\uc2  contacted him directly, a person familiar with the situation said, and is investing $500 million. The cryptocurrency exchange saw an opportunity to use the \uc2 blockchain\uc2 , a database for digital information, to help tackle bots, which are automated accounts that spam people, the person said.\par \par \uc2 ''A small contribution to the cause,'' \uc2 Changpeng Zhao\uc2 , \uc2 Binance\uc2 's founder, said 