\par\par \uc2 Money and Business/Financial Desk; SECTBU\par \b \uc2 The Tech Bubble That Won't Burst\b0\par\par\uc2 By Erin Griffith and Taylor Johnston \par \uc2 1,446 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 April 2022\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 8\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2022 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 The venture capitalists are sounding the alarm.\par \par \uc2 At posh conferences, they buzz about falling valuations for start-ups. On CNBC, they bemoan the sudden lack of initial public offerings. On \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , they warn of a coming downturn.\par \par \uc2 It is a familiar refrain. For the past decade, such warnings have cropped up repeatedly in start-up land. The industry is in another bubble, investors and commentators caution, conjuring the 1999 dot-com era and the dramatic collapse and recession that followed. Jobs disappeared, fortunes vaporized, and reputations were tarnished.\par \par \uc2 The message since has carried those scars: The boom times are ending. Buckle in for a rough ride.\par \par \uc2 Yet every time, more money has flooded into start-ups. Instead of a collapse, things got bubblier.\par \par \uc2 It started in 2011, when a tiny, elite group of start-ups attained ''unicorn'' status, with valuations of $1 billion or more.\par \par \uc2 Investors poured billions into start-ups each month; and hyped-up initial public offerings from \uc2 LinkedIn\uc2 , Pandora, \uc2 Zynga\uc2  and \uc2 Groupon\uc2  fueled fears of a bubble.\par \par \uc2 Steve Blank\par \par \uc2 Entrepreneur\par \par \uc2 ''We're now in the second Internet bubble. The signals are loud and clear.''\par \par \uc2 Lise Buyer\par \par \uc2 Founder of Class V Group\par \par \uc2 ''Yes, we have a frenzy again.''\par \par \uc2 The warnings didn't stick. Investors pumped $45 billion into U.S. start-ups that year.\par \par \uc2 Sean Parker\par \par \uc2 Entrepreneur and investor\par \par \uc2 ''I don't know how many more years of this we have -- maybe it's a year, a year or two, max.''\par \par \uc2 Facebook\uc2  went public in May 2012 with the largest-ever tech I.P.O. in the United States. Many viewed its valuation -- more than $100 billion for a start-up with less than $4 billion in revenue -- as a sign that tech valuations had ballooned out of control.\par \par \uc2 CNBC\par \par \uc2 Is the \uc2 Facebook\uc2  I.P.O. the Start of Another Tech Bubble?\par \par \uc2 NPR\par \par \uc2 Facebook\uc2  I.P.O.: Worth the Price or Next Internet Bubble?\par \par \uc2 The bubble they had warned of never burst.\par \par \uc2 Reuters\par \par \uc2 Web Start-Ups: The Dot-Com Bubble All Over Again?\par \par \uc2 Things sure felt bubbly. Engineers were demanding \uc2 Tesla\uc2  sports cars just for showing up to work, \uc2 Business Insider\uc2  presented as evidence.\par \par \uc2 The New York Times\par \par \uc2 If It Looks Like a Bubble and Floats Like a Bubble ...\par \par \uc2 By 2014, the number of unicorns around the world topped 90.\par \par \uc2 Marc Andreessen\par \par \uc2 Venture capitalist\par \par \uc2 ''Many high burn rate co's will VAPORIZE. ... Worry.''\par \par \uc2 The Wall Street Journal\par \par \uc2 Venture Capitalist Sounds Alarm on Start-Up Investing\par \par \uc2 Start-up investing rewards risk taking. Many of the most audacious, irrational investors have won by doubling down in a market frenzy. The cautious ones, trifling over such small-minded concerns as high prices or cash burn? Less so.\par \par \uc2 Suddenly \uc2 Uber\uc2  -- a little taxi app -- was worth $51 billion. More than \uc2 American Airlines\uc2  or \uc2 FedEx\uc2 , which actually turned profits. Investors blasted the alarm even louder.\par \par \uc2 Bill Gurley\par \par \uc2 Venture capitalist\par \par \uc2 ''You'll see some dead unicorns this year.''\par \par \uc2 Mark Cuban\par \par \uc2 Investor\par \par \uc2 ''This tech bubble is worse than the tech bubble of 2000''\par \par \uc2 The warnings were not all wrong -- a few unicorns did perish. (Remember \uc2 Fab.com\uc2  and Jawbone?)\par \par \uc2 But for every flameout, there were many more new ideas to back. New sources of capital -- including private equity, mutual funds and sovereign wealth funds -- began chasing unicorn investments. In May 2016, they poured $14.2 billion into more than 800 deals, the highest amount of the decade so far.\par \par \uc2 Keith Rabois\par \par \uc2 Venture capitalist\par \par \uc2 ''We're more back in the fear mode than the greed mode.''\par \par \uc2 Jim Breyer\par \par \uc2 Venture capitalist\par \par \uc2 There is ''blood in the water''; 90 percent of unicorns will be repriced or die.\par \par \uc2 Just in case the warnings were right, some investors lowered the valuations of their biggest investments, briefly cooling the unicorn frenzy. There was talk of onerous funding terms and start-up layoffs.\par \par \uc2 TechCrunch\par \par \uc2 The Top Unicorns Are Overvalued\par \par \uc2 Then \uc2 Masayoshi Son\uc2  arrived.\par \par \uc2 Masayoshi Son\par \par \uc2 SoftBank\uc2  chief executive\par \par \uc2 ''We only live once, so I want to think big. I have no intention of making small bets.''\par \par \uc2 The brazen investor dumped $100 billion into Silicon Valley start-ups -- dwarfing the rest of the venture capital market -- at a pace that averaged $100 million a day. Reuters called him a ''one-man bubble maker.'' Executives joked nervously about Mr. Son's ''capital cannon.'' \uc2 Venture\uc2  capital firms raised bigger funds to keep up.\par \par \uc2 Blockchain\uc2 !\par \par \uc2 MoviePass!\par \par \uc2 WeWork\uc2 !\par \par \uc2 Scooters!\par \par \uc2 High valuations and obscene spending became the norm. Start-ups prized growth over profits. Investors gave up on their bubble talk. Fear went out the window. Everyone decided to enjoy the party.\par \par \uc2 Research Affiliates\par \par \uc2 Yes. It's a Bubble. So What?\par \par \uc2 Annie Lamont\par \par \uc2 Venture capitalist\par \par \uc2 ''The fear of a correction is not occurring.''\par \par \uc2 Quartz\par \par \uc2 Investors Have Never Cared Less Whether an I.P.O. Makes Money\par \par \uc2 Venture funding soared, topping $26.9 billion in December and hitting a new yearly high of $143 billion. The unicorn count jumped to 348, according to PitchBook, which tracks the venture industry.\par \par \uc2 The Financial Times\par \par \uc2 Loss-Making Tech Companies Are Floating Like It's 1999\par \par \uc2 In the lead-up to its I.P.O., \uc2 WeWork\uc2  imploded. It was the kind of spectacular, embarrassing, humbling disaster that many thought would have ripple effects for years to come.\par \par \uc2 In boardrooms, investors murmured that this was really, truly, finally the end. On conference stages, start-up founders promised to ''pivot to profits.''\par \par \uc2 Travis VanderZanden\par \par \uc2 Chief executive of Bird\par \par \uc2 It is now difficult for ''a growth-at-all-costs company burning hundreds of millions of dollars with negative unit economics'' to get funding.\par \par \uc2 Then the pandemic hit. Prepare for tough times ahead, venture firms declared. For real this time.\par \par \uc2 That lasted barely a few weeks. Start-ups flourished in the pandemic and funding soared to new heights. I.P.O.s roared back. So, naturally, did the bubble talk.\par \par \uc2 Eric Paley\par \par \uc2 Venture capitalist\par \par \uc2 ''The party is as loud and the drinks are flowing as freely as the dot-com boom, despite that we're all drinking at home and alone.''\par \par \uc2 Rich Steinberg\par \par \uc2 Market strategist\par \par \uc2 ''It's silly season.''\par \par \uc2 More than 500 start-ups around the world topped $1 billion valuations. Those in the U.S. raised $164 billion in 2020, setting yet another record.\par \par \uc2 Meme stocks! Crypto! NFTs! SPACs! The \uc2 Federal Reserve\uc2  was printing money, interest rates were low, vaccines were available, and the world was set to reopen. By 2021, economists began predicting a new Roaring Twenties led by tech prosperity.\par \par \uc2 Yeah, it's probably a bubble, investors shrugged. But YOLO, amirite?\par \par \uc2 CNBC\par \par \uc2 'This Feels Like 1999': Global Start-Up Funding Frenzy Fuels Fears of a Bubble\par \par \uc2 Jeremy Grantham\par \par \uc2 Investment manager\par \par \uc2 ''This bubble will burst in due time.''\par \par \uc2 This year, fear crept in again, as interest rates were set to rise, inflation surged, and war broke out. Soon, tech stocks tanked. Initial public offerings screeched to a halt. Start-up investments fell.\par \par \uc2 A sense of caution returned. Was the bubble finally, really, truly bursting?\par \par \uc2 Today's warnings are different from those of the last decade. Investors tiptoe around the word ''bubble,'' referring instead to a ''recalibration,'' a ''pullback'' or even a gentle ''softening.'' The people who once called for caution grew tired of being wrong, and their audiences became numb to the warnings. Every time the alarm bells rang, more money poured into start-ups.\par \par \uc2 ''This time is different'' used to be a morbid joke among investors; now people believe it. Tech is too enmeshed in our lives, the thinking goes, and the dot-com bubble is too far in the rear view. This decade-long start-up boom has surged in the face of so many scares, each time amassing even more money and power. Maybe it really is different this time.\par \par \uc2 Some investors believe market euphorias are a good -- even necessary -- thing for progress. Without all that attention and excitement, how can a start-up founder convince workers and investors to help turn their crazy moonshot ideas into reality? Sure, most of the people who flock to a bubble are in it for the money. And yes, things can get messy. But underneath, it's all moving forward. Out of the dot-com ashes, techies like to remind us, grew \uc2 Amazon\uc2 , \uc2 PayPal\uc2  and \uc2 eBay\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Even as the biggest factor driving investors to high-growth start-ups over the last decade -- low interest rates -- begin to change, even as economists worry about an impending recession and even as start-ups lower their valuations or suddenly run out of cash, few today are predicting a total collapse.\par \par \uc2 A decade of talking about a bubble that never burst will do that.\par \par \uc2 (BU8-BU9) \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020220424ei4o00039\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw284\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4260\pichgoal600
