\par\par \uc2 Style Desk; SECTD\par \b \uc2 Building a New Community\b0\par\par\uc2 By Anna P. Kambhampaty and Sapna Maheshwari \par \uc2 1,496 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 March 2022\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2022 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 The Outdoor Voices founder has a new venture that aims to reward customers with \uc2 blockchain\uc2 -based assets. But do brand loyalists really want NFTs?\par \par \uc2 It would probably be a stretch to say that Ty Haney changed the way we work out. She didn't start a boutique fitness craze; she's not Jane Fonda. But Outdoor Voices, the athleisure company she founded in 2014, helped to popularize a fitness paradigm that has more to do with everyday movement than the body-stressing athleticism advertised by brands like \uc2 Nike\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Outdoor Voices built a following with color-blocked compression leggings and all-in-one exercise dresses that could easily transition from gym to brunch. On social media, fans boasted about buying items in every shade and posted pictures of themselves #DoingThings in scenic locales while wearing matching sets. They also shared feedback on new styles and colorways in online forums. It was a customer-loyalty fairy tale.\par \par \uc2 Though she is no longer with Outdoor Voices, Ms. Haney, 33, is hoping to bring its tenets of community building and consumer engagement into a new sphere: the \uc2 blockchain\uc2 -based future of the internet known as web3. She's betting that in the next phase of online retail, ''minting things'' will be the new ''doing things.''\par \par \uc2 Her latest venture, a platform called Try Your Best, will enable brands to collect input from customers in exchange for rewards such as digital collectibles (NFTs) and brand coins that can be used for bragging rights or toward purchases. These are assets, Ms. Haney said, that could potentially have lasting value, as opposed to the one-time discount codes and fleeting perks most companies offer loyalists.\par \par \uc2 ''The idea is that brands and fans build together, and the concept is to share value with those who create it,'' Ms. Haney said in an interview.\par \par \uc2 Direct-to-consumer brands have typically relied on disparate sources to solicit feedback from their most engaged customers: \uc2 Google\uc2  Docs, \uc2 Slack\uc2  bases, DMs. Try Your Best aims to streamline that process, and to route marketing dollars away from \uc2 Facebook\uc2  and \uc2 Instagram\uc2 , where Ms. Haney said that soaring costs have made it harder for emerging brands to grow.\par \par \uc2 So far, 10 brands have signed up for Try Your Best's pilot program, the company said, including Hill House Home, whose ''nap dresses'' became the height of pandemic loungewear, and Vada, a jewelry and eyewear company. But at the start, the only brand on the platform will be Joggy, a new brand led by Ms. Haney that sells products containing CBD and THCV.\par \par \uc2 She said that Try Your Best hopes to reach ''the Parade customer, the JuneShine customer, the Glossier customer -- these millennial, Gen Z-type audiences.''\par \par \uc2 The target users are ''the people who buy a brand because they love it and post about it on \uc2 Instagram\uc2 ,'' said Sean Judge, a general partner at Castle Island Ventures, which specializes in \uc2 blockchain\uc2 -related investments and put $2 million into Try Your Best -- a modest figure compared with Outdoor Voices' fund-raising. ''This is a way for them to connect with others in that community and also have a direct relationship with brands to provide real-time feedback around new product ideas and where the brand should head.''\par \par \uc2 Ms. Haney said that involving consumers in design decisions helped drive the success behind some of Outdoor Voices's most popular products. ''The way that we got people to buy every color -- 25 colors -- of the exercise dress was by bringing them upstream in the product creation process,'' she said, but ''there was really no centralized tool for this type of interaction.''\par \par \uc2 Casey Lewis, a trend researcher who writes about youth culture in her Substack newsletter, After School, was intrigued by the idea of brands rethinking customer loyalty but circumspect about the appeal of digital assets.\par \par \uc2 ''Any time a brand can successfully build a community, it's a huge win for them. But it's so, so hard to manufacture or force that success,'' Ms. Lewis said. ''The biggest question is: Do people care about NFTs, and will that be enough to get them involved and excited?''\par \par \uc2 Web3 has been billed, often in vague and utopian terms, as an online ecosystem where users will wrest power from the tech behemoths that dominate the current phase of the internet, Web 2.0.\par \par \uc2 Kevin Werbach\uc2 , a professor at the \uc2 Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania\uc2  and the author of ''The \uc2 Blockchain\uc2  and the New Architecture of Trust,'' said that while ''granting strong ownership rights directly to users'' could potentially shift the balance of power, none of web3's promises are guaranteed.\par \par \uc2 ''There's a web3 that's out there which is wonderful and trying to make the world a better place, but just by labeling something web3, it doesn't mean power dynamics will magically reverse,'' Professor Werbach said.\par \par \uc2 Ms. Haney is especially interested in bringing women into web3. ''We're seeing a predominantly male demo on Reddit and in Discords, telling each other about all of these opportunities,'' she said. ''By bringing brands that do have a large female audience base into crypto, that's a really big opportunity.''\par \par \uc2 Try Your Best runs on the Avalanche \uc2 blockchain\uc2 , which Ms. Haney said she chose in part because its transactions use significantly less energy than, say, Bitcoin or Ethereum. (Even supposedly ''green'' mining operations, however, are much more energy intensive than other financial transactions.)\par \par \uc2 Try Your Best plans to make money by collecting a monthly fee from brands and potentially sharing in revenue when tokens were used to drive sales.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Judge, the investor, previously worked with a range of direct-to-consumer companies, and heard constant frustration from them about the escalating costs of advertising to customers on \uc2 Facebook\uc2  and \uc2 Instagram\uc2 . Ms. Haney ''experienced these pain points firsthand,'' he said.\par \par \uc2 Outdoor Voices was a huge success. Ms. Haney and the company were the subject of a glowing feature in The New Yorker that compared Outdoor Voices to \uc2 Lululemon\uc2 , and it raised more than $50 million in venture capital. It also attracted the attention of \uc2 Mickey Drexler\uc2 , the retail legend who led transformations at Gap and J. Crew. He became chairman of the board and drew investors to the brand.\par \par \uc2 But just before the pandemic hit the United States, Ms. Haney's successful run at Outdoor Voices came to a screeching halt as investors questioned her leadership. A schism had opened between the young founder and Mr. Drexler, costly store openings were delayed, and a string of experienced retail executives left the company, which struggled with a relocation to Austin, Texas, from New York. The internal troubles were detailed in articles in \uc2 The New York Times\uc2  and BuzzFeed News.\par \par \uc2 Ms. Haney recalled thinking at the time, ''My life is going to be over.''\par \par \uc2 But as the news cycle moved on, so did she. ''It sucked but it didn't kill me, and it gave me that much more energy to go build again and show I can set vision and execute against it,'' she said. ''It feels good to take full accountability.''\par \par \uc2 Ms. Haney resigned from the brand in the investor tumult in February 2020 and then rejoined two months later with the title founder. In January 2021, she left the company and the board to pursue projects including Try Your Best. She still retains a stake in Outdoor Voices.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Judge was not concerned with Ms. Haney's tussle with investors at Outdoor Voices, and viewed it as a vote of confidence that several former employees of the firm have since joined her at Try Your Best.\par \par \uc2 ''There's challenges with every type of business, and some are more public than others,'' Mr. Judge said. ''I think Ty learned an incredible amount about building a business.''\par \par \uc2 Ms. Haney said that her start-up is arriving at a time when the traditional direct-to-consumer model -- which has built businesses like \uc2 Warby Parker\uc2 , Everlane and Glossier -- is ''broken'' after years of overreliance on social marketing.\par \par \uc2 At one point, she said, Outdoor Voices was devoting about 30 percent of its total funding to acquiring customers on \uc2 Facebook\uc2  and \uc2 Instagram\uc2 . She's hoping Try Your Best can help brands lower those costs.\par \par \uc2 Separately, as younger people may be less willing to hand over their thoughts and time for free, Try Your Best offers an answer to the question of how to pay them back.\par \par \uc2 ''One thing with Gen Z is they want to be rewarded for their input and advice,'' Ms. Lewis said. ''This is not a generation who is willing to do things just for the heck of it.''\par \par \uc2 Ty Haney has a project on web3, the \uc2 -based future of the internet. (D1); Ty Haney, above, of Try Your Best, which will enable brands like Joggy, left, to collect input from customers in exchange for rewards. (PHOTOGRAPHS BY CASSIDY ARAIZA FOR THE NEW YORK TIMES) (D4) \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020220317ei3h0002w\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw284\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4260\pichgoal600
