\par\par \uc2 Business/Financial Desk; SECTB\par \b \uc2 Biden Takes Step Toward Setting National Policy for Digital Assets\b0\par\par\uc2 By Katie Rogers and Ephrat Livni \par \uc2 1,097 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 March 2022\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2022 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 The president signed an executive order that will coordinate efforts among financial regulators to better understand the risks and opportunities presented by digital assets.\par \par \uc2 WASHINGTON -- President Biden signed an executive order on Wednesday directing the federal government to come up with a plan to regulate cryptocurrencies, recognizing their popularity and potential to destabilize traditional finance.\par \par \uc2 The order, under development for months, will coordinate efforts among financial regulators to better understand the risks and opportunities presented by digital assets, particularly in the areas of consumer protection, national security and illicit finance.\par \par \uc2 The move, according to the Biden administration, is a response to the ''explosive growth'' in digital assets, the increasing number of countries exploring central bank digital currencies and a desire to maintain American technological leadership. It directs financial regulators to continue with work that began in earnest last year, including studying and reporting on the creation of a digital dollar.\par \par \uc2 The results could help shape the contours of a rapidly innovating industry that has swiftly moved into the mainstream but that critics say enables illicit activity, including money laundering, and creates outsize financial risks for consumers and the financial system.\par \par \uc2 Brian Deese, the director of the National Economic Council, and Jake Sullivan, the president's national security adviser, said in a statement that the order ''will help position the U.S. to keep playing a leading role in the innovation and governance of the digital assets ecosystem at home and abroad, in a way that protects consumers, is consistent with our democratic values and advances U.S. global competitiveness.''\par \par \uc2 The directive calls on the government to assess the potential to develop a central bank digital currency -- essentially a digital dollar -- that would be used to modernize payment systems.\par \par \uc2 Central banks from the Bahamas to Sweden to China are experimenting with digital currency offerings, fueling concerns among lawmakers that the \uc2 Federal Reserve\uc2  might fall behind the competition.\par \par \uc2 In January, the Fed released a long-awaited report on central bank digital currencies, which it said was intended to generate debate. On Wednesday, after news of the executive order, the Fed's official \uc2 Twitter\uc2  account noted that it had ''made no decisions on whether to pursue or implement a central bank digital currency'' and invited the public to continue commenting on issues raised by its report.\par \par \uc2 Some, including the Fed chair, \uc2 Jerome H. Powell\uc2 , have argued that a U.S. digital dollar could eliminate the need for privately issued stablecoins -- digital currencies that promise to maintain their value by relying on stable financial backing like bank reserves and short-term debt. Private issuers resist that contention and have argued that they can coexist with a central digital currency, should one be developed.\par \par \uc2 Administration officials, who detailed the digital currency portion of the order for reporters on Wednesday, said the Fed's earlier report provided a strong foundation but did not attempt to resolve some of the trickier issues surrounding a digital dollar, including its design and issuance.\par \par \uc2 Treasury Department officials will now embark on a much more extensive examination of the digital dollar concept and the problems that could arise from it.\par \par \uc2 Eswar Prasad, a professor of trade policy at \uc2 Cornell University\uc2  and the author of a book called ''The Future of Money,'' said the order would put the United States in ''pole position'' to set global standards and move closer to what he said was ''the inevitable digitization of the world's pre-eminent currency.''\par \par \uc2 Experts on cryptocurrencies have long called for the government to streamline what had been a scattershot regulatory approach.\par \par \uc2 ''We need clear answers on how to do things,'' said Louis Lehot, a cryptocurrency expert at the law firm \uc2 Foley & Lardner\uc2 . ''We're operating in a gray zone and in a sandbox.''\par \par \uc2 He added, ''We've seen a complete lack of any strategic direction or thought from the federal government for years.''\par \par \uc2 The order comes at a moment of heightened national security concerns, including whether Russia will use cryptocurrency to evade punishing sanctions that the United States has imposed on President \uc2 Vladimir V. Putin\uc2 's regime as a result of his invasion of Ukraine. A senior Biden administration official who detailed the contents of the executive order but was not authorized to speak about it publicly told reporters on Tuesday evening that work on it had predated the Ukraine war.\par \par \uc2 Cryptocurrency would not be a viable way for Russia to circumvent sanctions, the official said, but the geopolitical situation exacerbates longstanding concerns about the role of anonymity in cryptocurrency and the risk of illicit activity that results. The \uc2 blockchain\uc2  technology underlying cryptocurrencies gives anyone who can read computer code the ability to track transactions, ostensibly eliminating the need for trust between transacting parties and allowing for anonymity.\par \par \uc2 Names and personal identifying information are not always required to participate in the crypto economy: On many decentralized platforms, programs and apps, code runs the show. The industry's offerings are attracting ever more money to projects that defy traditional business definitions, and increasingly vast amounts of digital assets are being managed by major players -- including venture capitalists and developers -- who operate without sharing their names.\par \par \uc2 Regulators have yet to write many rules surrounding the new technology, but Mr. Biden's executive order could change that.\par \par \uc2 Anticipation of a regulatory crackdown, along with rules requiring tougher scrutiny of digital transactions that were tucked into Mr. Biden's $1 trillion infrastructure bill, has prompted the cryptocurrency industry to beef up its lobbying presence in Washington.\par \par \uc2 Some groups promoting digital assets welcomed the order. ''The fact that the U.S. president has something to say about crypto is meaningful,'' said Kristin Smith, the executive director of the \uc2 Blockchain\uc2  Association, an industry trade group.\par \par \uc2 Senator \uc2 Patrick J. Toomey\uc2 , Republican of Pennsylvania and a cryptocurrency champion, directed unusual praise toward the White House for highlighting the potential benefits of cryptocurrencies, including stablecoins. But he warned that regulatory overreach could stymie growth in an area where innovation has been led by consumers.\par \par \uc2 ''This technology empowers individuals, and they deserve to have a say in crafting thoughtful legislation,'' Mr. Toomey said in a statement. ''The administration should resist the urge to stretch existing laws in an effort to expand its regulatory authority.''\par \par \uc2 David Yaffe-Bellany contributed reporting.\par \par \uc2 David Yaffe-Bellany contributed reporting.\par \par \uc2 The move by the Biden administration is a response to what it called the ''explosive growth'' in digital assets. (PHOTOGRAPH BY Tom Brenner for The New York Times FOR THE NEW YORK TIMES) \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020220310ei3a0003s\par }\page {\par\fs20{