\par\par \uc2 The Arts/Cultural Desk; SECTC\par \b \uc2 A Digital Artist Now Covers Walls Instead of Screens\b0\par\par\uc2 By Zachary Small \par \uc2 786 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 March 2022\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2022 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 The digital artist known for NFTs is showing paintings and prints IRL at a Manhattan gallery. Will the art establishment finally take notice?\par \par \uc2 A cavalry of crypto enthusiasts funneled into Manhattan's TriBeCa neighborhood on Thursday evening, waiting outside Jack Hanley Gallery for a chance to meet their online art messiah in the flesh. In the mix were celebrities like Jimmy Fallon. It was a rock-star welcome for Mike Winkelmann, the digital artist known as Beeple, who was putting the final touches on his images of decapitated tech executives and haywire science experiments.\par \par \uc2 Last year Winkelmann, 40, introduced the world to NFTs (or nonfungible tokens), starting with the $69 million sale of his ''Everydays -- The First 5000 Days'' at a Christie's auction, which set cryptocurrency on a crash course with culture. Now he is seeking approval from the art establishment with his first gallery exhibition, called ''Uncertain Future,'' which intends to convince critics that his work has more substance than what they see onscreen.\par \par \uc2 ''I'm kind of in a weird position,'' Winkelmann said at the gallery that night. ''I'm an outsider in the traditional art world. I didn't really feel like that until recently because I have been making this work in the digital art community for a very long time.''\par \par \uc2 So Winkelmann has produced an exhibition on walls instead of screens, with 13 paintings and prints that imagine an apocalyptic future where companies like \uc2 Amazon\uc2  and \uc2 Facebook\uc2  are reduced to rubble, their founders vessels of vanity and greed. Prices range from $75,000 to $300,000. Not that any of the hundreds who attended had a chance of buying a Beeple on Thursday night; the artworks were all on reserve, purchased, by the time the doors opened.\par \par \uc2 Still, Winkelmann remains bullish on NFTs, pairing each physical work with a \uc2 blockchain\uc2 -based collectible for authentication purposes. He said that much of his fortune made off the metaverse has gone back into his art.\par \par \uc2 Winkelmann recently moved into a new 50,000-square-foot industrial studio space in Charleston, S.C. His younger brother, Scott Winkelmann, quit his job at the airplane company \uc2 Boeing\uc2  to oversee the 16 full-time employees responsible for turning the artist's dreams into realities. (The staff includes several aerospace engineers from \uc2 Boeing\uc2 .) Other family members have joined the team, including the sons' mother, who has an office within the studio complex.\par \par \uc2 Several advisers from the worlds of crypto and culture have also joined team Beeple, including Jehan Chu, a \uc2 blockchain\uc2  venture capitalist and NFT collector who attended the opening.\par \par \uc2 ''Right now, there are two art worlds,'' said Chu, adding that he hoped more museums and galleries would soften to digital art. ''The traditional art world is still learning about the fundamental values of the NFT space.''\par \par \uc2 Development for the exhibition started nine months ago with Winkelmann calling the gallerist Jack Hanley. ''I was initially suspicious of all the hype,'' the dealer said. ''But Mike has a really cleareyed critique of big tech. He's also very funny.''\par \par \uc2 Hanley has spent the last 35 years championing outsider artists like Raymond Pettibon and Peter Saul, who slowly gained institutional acceptance after being dismissed for lacking a formal arts education. Winkelmann could be the next generation, the dealer said, though not everyone at the gallery agrees; Hanley confirmed that some artists he represents quit in protest of the Beeple exhibition, as Artnet News had reported.\par \par \uc2 Fans say that Winkelmann's ability to shock the establishment is part of his appeal.\par \par \uc2 ''The essence of Beeple is kind of between a satirist and a troll,'' said Simon Glenn, 26, a web developer who was admiring a print that imagines a future \uc2 Netflix\uc2  reduced to broken television sets and rusting cargo containers. ''It's asking what the company would be like without its people.''\par \par \uc2 Toward the back of the gallery, the artist Julia Sinelnikova, 32, was admiring a large painting that features the disfigured head of Jeff Bezos quarantined within an ''excess testosterone dump.'' She appreciated that Winkelmann was willing to critique the leaders of an industry that has supported his work.\par \par \uc2 ''I had been looking at Beeple's work for a long time just as entertainment,'' Sinelnikova said, squinting at the artist's phallus-filled portrait of the \uc2 Amazon\uc2  founder. ''But the works here in the gallery are much more beautiful and detailed than I expected.''\par \par \uc2 Mike Winkelmann, top center, also known as Beeple, at the Jack Hanley Gallery in Manhattan. His artwork on display there, above, is paired with nonfungible tokens for authentication purposes. (PHOTOGRAPHS BY LANDON NORDEMAN FOR THE NEW YORK TIMES) \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020220305ei3500031\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw284\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4260\pichgoal600
