\par\par \uc2 Business/Financial Desk; SECTB\par \b \uc2 Twitter\uc2  Wants to Reinvent Itself by Shifting Online Power to Its Users\b0\par\par\uc2 By Kate Conger \par \uc2 1,663 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 March 2022\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2022 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 In 2008, the handful of employees working for \uc2 Twitter\uc2  reached an impasse. Some were focused on preparing for a surge of new users to their social media platform. But one developer argued for another approach: Their platform, he said, shouldn't be a platform at all.\par \par \uc2 Instead, Blaine Cook envisioned \uc2 Twitter\uc2  as a backbone for online chatter, one that would allow its users to freely exchange messages with people on other social media platforms instead of locking them into conversations among themselves. He hacked together a prototype to demonstrate his idea.\par \par \uc2 But the other \uc2 Twitter\uc2  employees dismissed it, and Mr. Cook was eventually pushed out of the start-up. \uc2 Twitter\uc2  remained a tightly controlled island on the internet and eventually drew in hundreds of millions of users.\par \par \uc2 Now, over a decade later, \uc2 Twitter\uc2  is reversing course. The company is pursuing the sort of decentralization Mr. Cook championed. It is funding an independent effort to build a so-called open protocol for social media. It is also weaving cryptocurrency into its app, and opening up to developers who want to build custom features for \uc2 Twitter\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Its newly appointed chief executive, \uc2 Parag Agrawal\uc2 , has championed decentralization inside the company, hiring cryptocurrency developers and prioritizing related projects. \uc2 Twitter\uc2  executives now believe that decentralizing the social media service will radically shift online power, moving it into the hands of users, and pose a fundamental challenge to the walled gardens of companies like \uc2 Facebook\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 A decentralized \uc2 Twitter\uc2  could take years to emerge and might look much the same as it does today. But it could allow users to set moderation rules for their own communities and ease the pressure \uc2 Twitter\uc2  faces from lawmakers over how it moderates content. It might also open new revenue streams for the company.\par \par \uc2 ''If Bitcoin existed before \uc2 Twitter\uc2  existed, I think we'd see very different revenue models,'' \uc2 Jack Dorsey\uc2 , a company co-founder who stepped down as its chief executive in November, said in a recent \uc2 Twitter\uc2  audio chat. ''We wouldn't be so dependent on ad revenue models.''\par \par \uc2 But the changes raise questions about how \uc2 Twitter\uc2  can reach its goal of doubling revenue over the next two years, even as it cedes some control over the currency by which social media companies are valued -- users and their data. \uc2 Twitter\uc2  also faces some doubts from the communities it hopes to unite: slighted developers, web3 acolytes and enthusiasts for open-source software.\par \par \uc2 The impulse to build decentralized systems is rooted in the foundation of the internet, with open protocols like the one Mr. Cook envisioned for \uc2 Twitter\uc2  at the heart of everyday technologies like email. \uc2 Twitter\uc2  is looking back at how the company started and how it strayed, and it is trying to tap into that old idealism for a new kind of business.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Dorsey said he was drawn to decentralized technologies like Bitcoin because they reminded him of the ethos of the early internet. ''It had the same sort of energy, it had the weirdness, it had the punk aspect of it,'' Mr. Dorsey said in the \uc2 Twitter\uc2  audio chat.\par \par \uc2 In a recent interview, Mr. Cook, who is now an engineer at Cond\u233\'00\'E9 Nast, said, ''It was obvious that we could decentralize \uc2 Twitter\uc2 .''\par \par \uc2 Over the years, he watched as the company grappled with many of the problems he thought could have been avoided through decentralization: regulatory challenges, debates over acceptable speech, and fights over which features to develop.\par \par \uc2 In 2019, Mr. Dorsey decided to decentralize \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , after discussions with Mr. Agrawal, then \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's chief technology officer, about the challenges facing the company.\par \par \uc2 That December, Mr. Dorsey announced his plan to fund the Bluesky project. ''\uc2 Twitter\uc2  was so open early on that many saw its potential to be a decentralized internet standard,'' Mr. Dorsey tweeted. ''For a variety of reasons, all reasonable at the time, we took a different path and increasingly centralized \uc2 Twitter\uc2 .''\par \par \uc2 The Bluesky project would eventually allow for the creation of new curation algorithms, which would show tweets at the top of users' timelines that differed from what \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's own algorithm showed. It would give users more choice about the kinds of content they saw, Mr. Dorsey said, and could allow \uc2 Twitter\uc2  to interoperate with other social media services.\par \par \uc2 Bluesky grabbed the attention of many technologists who were already working on decentralization. Soon small groups of them were meeting with Mr. Agrawal and Mr. Dorsey on Sundays to discuss the project, according to two participants who spoke on the condition of anonymity to discuss the private meetings, while others traded ideas in an online chat room.\par \par \uc2 Some Bluesky participants proposed a single app that piped in all their social media feeds. Others wanted custom algorithms that could, for instance, block them from seeing spoilers about their favorite TV show. And some were focused on making their online identities portable, so that an account could be moved between social media companies the way a phone number can be moved from \uc2 AT&T\uc2  to \uc2 Verizon\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 ''One of the things that Bluesky would offer is curation and filtering experiences that are independent of those offered by the social media proprietorships,'' said Tim Bray, an internet software pioneer and a former vice president at \uc2 Amazon\uc2  who participated in some of the discussions.\par \par \uc2 Jay Graber, a cryptocurrency developer, was selected in August to lead the Bluesky organization. And in February, Ms. Graber announced that the project had officially registered as a public benefit corporation and was building a prototype.\par \par \uc2 The project caught the attention of engineers at Reddit, who had preliminary discussions with \uc2 Twitter\uc2  engineers about how their sites might someday interoperate, two people familiar with the conversations said, but the companies have not formally agreed to any plans to work together.\par \par \uc2 Some skeptics believe \uc2 Twitter\uc2  is jumping on the web3 bandwagon, joining a trendy movement in tech to shift many services, including social media, to so-called \uc2 blockchain\uc2  technology. But executives say \uc2 Twitter\uc2  is catering to what an overwhelming number of users want, while following the decentralization mandate that Mr. Dorsey laid out before he departed as chief executive in November.\par \par \uc2 ''The crypto community lives on \uc2 Twitter\uc2 ,'' said Esther Crawford, a staff product manager who oversees \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's web3 efforts. ''To ignore that community or disregard it is a missed opportunity.''\par \par \uc2 In September, Ms. Crawford led \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's expansion of its tipping feature, allowing users to pay one another in cash or Bitcoin. And in January, the company began allowing paying users to display NFTs -- cryptographic collectibles that represent pieces of digital art -- as their profile pictures. (Lest anyone mistake a regular profile picture for an NFT, \uc2 Twitter\uc2  displays NFT profile pictures with a unique hexagonal border.)\par \par \uc2 In December, conversations about NFTs made up 1.2 percent of the entire conversation on \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , a company spokeswoman said. Users sent more than 220 million tweets about NFTs in 2021, making them a larger conversation topic than movies, which generated about 207 million tweets.\par \par \uc2 Ms. Crawford added that \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's embrace of cryptocurrencies had a practical explanation. For years, the company has been growing more rapidly outside the United States than within it, and allowing users to exchange money across borders will help facilitate that growth.\par \par \uc2 In November, \uc2 Twitter\uc2  expanded unpaid access to its fire hose of data, inviting developers to create new ways for users to interact with the platform. Tracy Chou, the chief executive of the anti-harassment tool Block Party, uses access to \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's data to build features that filter abusive messages out of a user's \uc2 Twitter\uc2  notifications. Her work represents the kind of custom experience that \uc2 Twitter\uc2  might not build in-house but still wants for its users.\par \par \uc2 ''If we just look at where the platforms are now in terms of addressing online harms, they are not doing a very good job,'' Ms. Chou said. ''An algorithm that is the best overall, an average best experience, definitely is still going to leave out a lot of people who don't like that experience.''\par \par \uc2 But while \uc2 Twitter\uc2  has given developers like Ms. Chou the data they need to build custom experiences, the company has also yanked it away. It has locked down the kinds of data that developers use several times, most recently in 2018, when it limited access to its application programming interface, or A.P.I., effectively breaking a number of smaller companies' apps.\par \par \uc2 Anil Dash, who helped found ThinkUp, a company that relied on data from \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , \uc2 Facebook\uc2  and \uc2 Instagram\uc2 , recalled telling \uc2 Twitter\uc2  executives that they had effectively killed his company by cutting off data access.\par \par \uc2 ''Developers do not trust them,'' Mr. Dash said. ''You are Lucy with the football and we are Charlie Brown, and you have pulled the football away 100 times.''\par \par \uc2 Mr. Dash, who is now the chief executive of Glitch, said \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's decentralization strategy hinged on its ability to woo developers back. ''It's not insurmountable, but it's the fundamental condition of this entire strategy succeeding: Convince the most skeptical audience to trust them again.''\par \par \uc2 Amir Shevat, \uc2 Twitter\uc2 's head of product for developers, got the job by offering similar criticism to Mr. Dorsey and Mr. Agrawal. At the time, he was a top executive at Reshuffle, a developer platform. But after discussions about developer access, the \uc2 Twitter\uc2  executives agreed to acquire Reshuffle last March.\par \par \uc2 ''Talking to Jack and Parag, they recognized that \uc2 Twitter\uc2  before was a lot more open,'' Mr. Shevat said in an interview. He added, ''I think what you're seeing is a move back into that.''\par \par \uc2 ''If you decentralize your platform and you give developers more powers to make richer experiences and better, safer timelines, then everybody benefits from this,'' he also said.\par \par \uc2 ''It was obvious that we could decentralize Twitter,'' said Blaine Cook, who championed a so-called open protocol during the company's early days. (PHOTOGRAPH BY AMANDA MARY FOR THE NEW YORK TIMES) (B5) \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020220304ei340003b\par }\par }}